The [[acronym]] '''SMIDSY''' (for "sorry mate, I didn't see you") is used by British motorcyclists and cyclists to describe [[traffic accident|collisions]] in which a car driver fails to perceive a two-wheel user.

The word perceive is chosen with care.  There is good evidence that drivers may in fact see at the subconscious level, but that this is not translated to the conscious as the brain does not perceive the other as a threat.

These collisions may be recorded as ''failure to see'', or as simply ''[[right of way]] violations''.  Right of way violations are a significant cause of serious and fatal injury to both groups; they are typically characterised by a motor vehicle entering or crossing the traffic, violating the injured party's right of way.  It has been suggested that motorcyclists are unusually likely to commit such violations against pedal cyclists, but evidence is contradictory.

